                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            
                            <p>Letter from the War Office, London to the under-secretary, Sir Matthew Nathan (1862-1939), regarding the issuing of permits for civilians from Government Departments travelling to the British Zone at the front.  The letter suggests that a regulation, similar to those in force in the War Office (â€˜Permits for Civilians Proceeding to France on Duty' which is attached) should be established in each Department. </p>
                            
                        
                            
                        
                            
                            <p>Sir Matthew Nathan was the under-secretary for Ireland from 1914 to 1916. In 1916 Nathan offered his resignation following the outbreak of the Easter Rising.</p>
                            
                        
                    
                </note>
